.Software Development Methodologies
Software Development Methodologies are structured approaches used to plan, develop, test, and deliver software projects efficiently.
They help teams organize work, manage time, reduce risks, and deliver quality software.
Common Software Development Methodologies
1. Waterfall Model
This is a traditional and linear approach where each phase is completed before moving to the next one.
Phases:
Requirement Analysis
Design
Development
Testing
Deployment
Maintenance
Advantages
Simple and easy to understand
Good for small and fixed projects
Disadvantages
Difficult to make changes later
Not suitable for changing requirements
2. Agile Methodology
Agile is an iterative and flexible approach where development happens in small parts called sprints.
Each sprint usually lasts 1–4 weeks.
Advantages
Quick delivery
Easy to handle changing requirements
Better customer feedback
Disadvantages
Requires continuous communication
Can be difficult without proper planning
3. Scrum
Scrum is a framework under Agile.
It uses short development cycles called sprints and includes regular meetings like:
Sprint Planning
Daily Standup
Sprint Review
Retrospective
Roles:
Product Owner
Scrum Master
Development Team
4. DevOps
DevOps combines development and operations to improve collaboration and automate software delivery.
Focus areas:
CI/CD
Automation
Monitoring
Fast deployment
Tools often used:
Git
Jenkins
Docker
Kubernetes
5. Spiral Model
This model combines design and prototyping with strong risk analysis.
It is used for large and high-risk projects.
Advantages
Better risk management
Suitable for complex systems
Disadvantages
Expensive
Complex to manage
6. V-Model (Verification and Validation Model)
This is an extension of the Waterfall model where testing is planned parallel to development.
Each development stage has a corresponding testing stage.
Advantage
Strong testing process
Disadvantage
Not flexible for changing requirements

